<HEADLINE> German Upper House Rejects Tax Reform Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Germany's upper house of parliament,
controlled by the main opposition Social Democrats (SPD), today
rejected as expected the Bonn government's 30 billion mark (17.6
billion U.S. dollar) tax reform bill.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesrat described the government's 1999 tax reform
package as financially shaky, socially imbalanced and off-target
in economic policy terms.
</P>
<P>
German Finance Minister Theo Waigel refuted the criticism
during the debate, saying the plans showed social balance and
would give relief to wage earners.
</P>
<P>
On June 26, the bill is expected to be presented to the
Bundestag, the lower house of parliament, where Chancellor Helmut
Kohl's center-right coalition government enjoys a 10-seat
majority. If the Bundestag passes the bill, the Bundesrat will
have to resolve the matter by mediation.
</P>
<P>
The SPD and the Bonn government held negotiations on a
compromise in late April, which ended in failure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
