<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's No.2 Most Wanted Mafia Boss Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALERMO, Sicily, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Pietro Aglieri, the
notorious No.2 Mafia godfather, was arrested this morning in a
raid by the police at Bagheria near Palermo.
</P>
<P>
Natale Gambino and Giuseppe La Mattina, two mob hitmen, were
also arrested in the sting which involved around 100 police
officers and 200 agents.
</P>
<P>
The operation was hailed as a severe blow to the organized
crime gangs and as the most important Mafia arrest since that of
Sicilian boss Giovanni Brusca last year.
</P>
<P>
"This very important success is the concrete proof that the
state is fully committed to the fight against the Mafia," said
deputy Prime Minister Walter Veltroni.
</P>
<P>
Aglieri has been accused of involvement in the car bomb
killings of magistrates Paolo Borsellino and Giovanni Falcone in
1992 as well as of former European parliamentarian and leading
Christian Democratic politician Salvo Lima who was gunned down in
the same year.
</P>
<P>
Aglieri, who will be 38 in three days time, has been sentenced
in absentia to life in prison for the murder of judge Antonino
Scopelliti in August 1991 and to 12 years for drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
La Mattina has also been sentenced to life while Gambino has
been sentenced to 10 years in jail.
</P>
<P>
Aglieri had been on the run since December 1989 and is
considered by investigators to be the right-hand man of Bernardo
Provenzano, the most wanted Mafia boss still at large, and ally of
godfather Salvatore "The Beast" Riina, who was captured in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
