<HEADLINE> European Social Democrats Gather in Sweden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Nine of the European Union's 15
prime ministers have gathered in the southern Swedish city of
Malmo for a European Social Democratic party congress.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 delegates have attended the three-day conference
since Thursday where leaders of Europe's social democrats have
been trying to harmonize their ideas ahead of an EU summit in
Amsterdam on June 16-17.
</P>
<P>
Employment, environment, education, and EU enlargement are the
top four fields social democrats must deal with, said Swedish
Prime Minister Goran Persson at the opening session of the
congress.
</P>
<P>
After Tony Blair's Labor Party won the British election and
Lionel Jospin's Socialists followed with a win in the French
election last weekend, 13 of the 15 EU member states are now
governed by center or center-left administrations.
</P>
<P>
But the shadow of the European Union's single currency hung
over the conference, with Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok and Persson
sparring at a news conference about Sweden's decision not to join
economic and monetary union.
</P>
<P>
Kok said he regretted Sweden's decision not to join but would
accept it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
