<HEADLINE> Ireland Voices Concern Over Radioactive Lobsters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Irish government has expressed
grave concern over the "objectionable discharges" from a British
nuclear plant, which may have turned some lobsters in the Irish
Sea to become radioactive.
</P>
<P>
Irish Minister of State at the Department of Transport and
Energy Emmet Stagg was quoted by press reports from Dublin as
saying today that he was deeply concerned about the high levels of
radioactive Technetium 99 in the Irish Sea close to Britain's
Sellafield nuclear reprocessing plant.
</P>
<P>
"I will pursue these issues relentlessly with the British
authorities and demand an early resolution to these objectionable
discharges and other problems," Stagg said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Irish minister also noted that he had requested an early
meeting with British government officials "to pursue this specific
problem."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Nuclear Fuels (BNFL) has repeatedly
dismissed the Irish government's allegations that discharges from
the plant were turning lobsters radioactive.
</P>
<P>
The Dublin government, which has long been worried about
discharges from the Sellafield nuclear plant, in February called
on the British ambassador to Ireland to lodge a complaint after
two incidents within 24 hours at the British nuclear plant.
</P>
</TEXT>
