<DOCNO> XIE19970607.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of England Raises Interest to Curb Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 6 (xinhua) -- The Bank of England's newly
appointed monetary policy committee raised official rates to 6.5
percent from 6.25 percent after its meeting today.
</P>
<P>
The committee spent a whole day Thursday discussing interest
rates and announced its decision at noon today, said reports.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time since the central bank was nationalized
in 1945 that it had changed interest rates without being
instructed by the government.
</P>
<P>
The bank said recent economic data were consistent with the
view it took in its Inflation Report last month that "on present
evidence, there is still likely to be a need for some further
moderate tightening of policy in the months ahead."
</P>
<P>
"The committee accordingly voted to raise the bank's reporate
by 0.25 percent to 6.25 percent," the bank said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Confederation of British Industry (CBI) had urged the bank
to hold fire on interest rates until after next month's budget.
</P>
<P>
With its latest survey of retailers, the CBI said that annual
growth in sales volumes fell to its lowest rate for a year and a
half.
</P>
<P>
"The slowdown in sales growth reported in May is disappointing
for retailers," said Alastair Eperon, chairman of the CBI's
distributive trades panel.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey indicated that looking at the retail sector
as a whole, the three month average balance of retailers reporting
higher sales volumes stood at 32 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
It showed that "underlying sales remain on a firmly upward
track and retailers are optimistic about business over the short
term," Eperon added.
</P>
<P>
Although the underlying trend in retail sales remained on an
upward track, the CBI said that inflationary pressures were still
being restrained by intense price competition among retailers.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the bank's announcement, Britain's two
biggest lenders, the Abbey National and Halifax, upped mortgage
rates by 0.35 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that the action to tighten the monetary stance,
taken with the aim of meeting the government's inflation target,
"offers the best chance of achieving continued growth in output
and employment at a sustainable pace." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
