<DOCNO> XIE19970607.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Impact of Technology on Futures, Options Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Futures and Options Association
(FOA) published today a study into the broad technology issues
facing futures and options market participants, exchanges,
regulators and system providers.
</P>
<P>
The FOA is a London-based trade association for firms,
institutions and exchanges involved in futures and options
business.
</P>
<P>
It has an international membership of 200 banks and other
financial institutions, commodity trade houses, brokers,
exchanges, clearing houses, fund managers, corporate treasuries
and specialist firms which provide legal and accountancy services
to market participants.
</P>
<P>
The study is the first of its kind to access the impact of
technology on the futures and options industry and the changes
likely to take place over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
It provides a valuable insight into the issues facing various
segments of the market and their participants.
</P>
<P>
Technology promises to confer a competitive advantage on those
willing to incur the substantial risks and costs of being at the
forefront of developments.
</P>
<P>
But it will cut out those middle-men in the industry who
provide no more than a data-routing processing services, according
to the study.
</P>
<P>
It said that technology has the potential to lower costs and
enhance service levels, but the lack of industry standards will
hamper this trend.
</P>
<P>
Michael Jenkins, chairman of the FOA, said at the Fourth
International Derivatives Conference which ended today, "Despite a
preference by many exchanges for open outcry trading, it is
supported by the sophisticated use of technology, placing the
industry in the vanguard of innovation."
</P>
<P>
"But the industry is changing as fast as technology, and this
poses particularly difficult issues, which will need to be tackled
now," he added. 
</P>
