<HEADLINE> 2,252 PKK Rebels Killed in Turkey's Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish high-ranking military
officer said today that 2,252 rebels of the illegal Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) have been killed since the Turkish government
troops launched cross-border military operations in northern Iraq
on May 14.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, Erol Ozkasnak, secretary
general of the Turkish General Staff, said that the Turkish
security forces also wounded 289 PKK guerrillas in their military
campaign, which is still going on in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish incursion followed a request for aid by Iraq's
Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) leader Mesud Barzani to attack
the PKK.
</P>
<P>
Ozkasnak said that 95 military personnel, including 13
officers and 21 village guards were killed and 244 others wounded
in the massive military operations.
</P>
<P>
The security forces also captured a large quantity of various
kinds of weapons worth at least 2.65 million U.S. dollars from
the PKK camps and bases in northern Iraq, said Ozkasnak.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Turkish government troops had
controlled the PKK camps in the areas of Sinath, Haftanin,
Hayirsiz Dag, Beyaz Dag, Haruna, Metina, Zap, Gara Dagi in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Khalil Attachi, leader of the PKK, was quoted by a newspaper
as saying in Lebanon Monday that his group would attack Israeli
and U.S. targets in Turkish cities and tourist areas.
</P>
<P>
Attachi said that his organization would "carry out operations
against Israeli targets in Istanbul (Turkey's largest city), and
elsewhere in Turkey and against the U.S. enemy interests."
</P>
<P>
More than 23,000 people, including PKK members, civilians and
government troops, have been killed in conflicts since the PKK
started a separatist war for self-rule in eastern and
southeastern Turkey in August 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
