<HEADLINE> Blair, Kohl Urge Closer UK-German Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Visiting British Prime Minister Tony
Blair and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl both expressed the hope
today for closer ties and cooperation between their two countries.
</P>
<P>
During their talks of two hours in the German chancellory, the
two leaders discussed issues concerning the single European
currency, the euro, which is planned to be launched from 1999.
</P>
<P>
Among topics of their discussion were also the meeting of NATO
leaders scheduled for early July in Madrid and the summit meeting
of the world's top seven industrialized nations in Denver, the
Unites States.
</P>
<P>
Blair arrived in Bonn from a meeting of Europe's Social
Democrats in Melmo, Sweden. He was welcomed by Kohl for his first
meeting with a foreign head of government since taking office a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
Before their meeting, Kohl told reporters that he saw the talks
with Blair as an expression of their common will to strengthen
bilateral ties. For Germans it was of fundamental importance to
travel the path to the future "in partnership with our British
friends as we have done in the last 40 years," said Kohl.
</P>
<P>
Blair stressed that a warm and strong UK-German relationship
was in the interest not only of the two countries, but also of
Europe and the world.
</P>
<P>
Kohl also expressed confidence that the upcoming European Union
summit meeting in Amsterdam 10 days later would be successful.
Blair said Britain would work hard for the success of the summit,
which is to prepare for the EU enlargement to Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister said that EU expansion was "vitally
important for peace and stability in the world." 
</P>
