<HEADLINE> Germany to Suspend Repatriating Refugees From  Serbian-Controlled Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Germany will not for the time being
force the return of Bosnian refugees originating from
Serbian-controlled territory, it was decided at a meeting of
interior ministers today.
</P>
<P>
Federal Interior Minister Manfred Kanther and his counterparts
from Germany's 16 states agreed that the return of Bosnian and
Croatian refugees to their homeland that is now Serbian-controlled
was a sensitive issue. Therefore, repatriation of them "should be
regarded as low priority," they said.
</P>
<P>
Germany has taken in about 320,000 Bosnian refugees, about
30,000 of them having voluntarily left. About 150,000 of the
refugees remaining in Germany were from the Serbian-controlled
territory.
</P>
<P>
Kanther described the refugees as Germany's "temporary guests"
who would eventually have to return to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
He also denied allegations of mass expulsions of Bosnian
refugees, saying only 269 people had so far been forced to return,
about half of whom had criminal records. 
</P>
</TEXT>
