<HEADLINE> Troops, Rebels Confront in Capital of Republic of Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Confrontation continued today in the
capital of the Republic of Congo between troops loyal to President
Pascal Lissouba and the rebels supporting former President Denis
Sassou Nguesso, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The French ambassador, who returned to Brazzaville from Paris
this morning, was escorted to the French embassy by French
soldiers stationed in the city, reported Agence France-Presse
(AFP).
</P>
<P>
Brazzaville is now divided into two parts, one controlled by
the supporters of Lissouba, and the other by those of Nguesso, who
set up a confrontation line along the Avenue of Peace, the city's
main thoroughfare, said AFP.
</P>
<P>
Gunfires were heard throughout the day today, after the
government imposed a curfew Thursday evening following one day of
fighting between the soldiers supporting the two factions, said
AFP.
</P>
<P>
Telephone connection between Brazzaville and the outside is now
cut by the government, who accused the rebels of creating a chaos
in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Government troops, backed by armored vehicles, surrounded the
residence of Nguesso Thursday morning and clashed with gunmen
protecting the former president, who ruled Congo from 1979 to 1992
and is now running for the presidential election scheduled for
July.
</P>
<P>
Some government troops have reportedly rallied with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Congo was plunged into chaos in 1993 after holding its
legislative election, whose results were disputed by supporters of
Nguesso. Thousands of people were killed in the violence in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
