<HEADLINE> China Notifies UN on Conventions that Apply to HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador Wang
Xuexian today sent notices to UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan that
10 international conventions, to which China has acceded, will
apply to Hong Kong with effect from July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Wang, acting permanent representative of China to the UN, said
in the notices that Hong Kong will enjoy a high degree of
autonomy, except in foreign and defense affairs, after China
resumes the exercise of sovereignty from July 1, 1997 in
accordance with the Sino-British Joint Declaration signed on
December 19, 1984.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said that today's notices cover the first
batch of international conventions that will apply to Hong Kong
with effect from July 1. Chinese diplomats were working hard to
prepare documents on other conventions that will apply to Hong
Kong after its return to China.
</P>
<P>
The Government of the People's Republic of China will assume
responsibilities for the international rights and obligations
arising from the application of the conventions to Hong Kong,
according to the Chinese ambassador.
</P>
<P>
The 10 conventions covered by today's notices are as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- the Single Convention on Narcotic Drugs, 1961, as amended by
the Protocol of 25 March 1972 Amending the Single Convention on
Narcotic Drugs, 1961;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention on Psychotropic Substances;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime
of Genocide;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime
against Internationally Protected Persons, including Diplomatic
Agents;
</P>
<P>
-- the International Convention against the Taking of Hostages;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention on the Recognition and Enforcement of Foreign
Arbitral Awards;
</P>
<P>
-- the Customs Conventions on Containers 1972;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention on Registration of Objects Launched into
Outer Space;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention on a Code of Conduct for Liner Conferences;
and
</P>
<P>
-- the Vienna Convention for the Protection of the Ozone Layer
and the Montreal Protocol on Substances that Deplete the Ozone
Layer of 16 September 1987 and the Amendment to the Montreal
Protocol on Substances that Deplete the Ozone Layer adopted at
London on June 29, 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
