<HEADLINE> Egypt Supports Establishment of Arab Common </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 6 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian diplomat stressed here
today his country's support for the establishment of an Arab
common market aimed at counteracting what the Arabs fear of an
Israeli economic hegemony in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
Adel Al-Khodri, Egypt's ambassador to Lebanon, met with
Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz in the latter's office
today.
</P>
<P>
He said after the meeting that the discussions were
"concentrated on the Arab economic coalition" mentioned by Syrian
Vice-President Abdel Halim Khaddam here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We in Egypt are totally supporting the establishment of an
Arab common market," Al-Khodri said, adding that Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak is doing his best "to push the idea."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Egyptian government has begun seriously
thinking about the idea after it was put forward at first by Arab
parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian envoy said that the idea is currently being
studied by Egypt and Syria in detail and the two countries will
present it, as the first stage, to a conference of the Damascus
Declaration states, which is to be held in the Syrian capital on
June 25.
</P>
<P>
But the diplomat denied that his country has taken a position
on an Arab economic conference, which was raised by Syria to
replace the Middle East economic summit scheduled for November in
Doha, Qatar, to which Israel is invited.
</P>
<P>
Following his talks with Lebanese President Elias Hrawi and
other Lebanese officials here Thursday, the Syrian vice-
president stressed the need for an Arab economic coalition which
would help Arab countries "face the various developments that we
are currently undergoing."
</P>
<P>
He said both Syria and Egypt had decided to prepare a joint
working paper to be submitted later this month to a foreign
minister meeting of the Damascus Declaration states, which
include the two countries and the six Gulf Arab states.
</P>
</TEXT>
