<HEADLINE> Germany Puts Scientology Under Intelligence Surveillance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Germany announced today that it would
put activities of the Scientology organization under the scrutiny
of the intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
German Interior Minister Manfred Kanther and his counterparts
from Germany's 16 states made the decision at a meeting after
hearing reports on operations in Germany of the organization,
which was founded in the United States in 1954.
</P>
<P>
Kanther said that the country's intelligence service, the
Office for the Protection of the Constitution, had concluded from
collected information that the Scientology organization aimed at
winning political power and influence to influence society in an
"absolutist" way.
</P>
<P>
The interior chiefs agreed that a surveillance report should be
presented in a year.
</P>
<P>
No details concerning the surveillance were released. Kanther
ensured that there would be no "witch hunt" or moves to proscribe
the organization.
</P>
<P>
The Scientology organization does not have religious status in
Germany and has been judicially proclaimed a profit-oriented
enterprise. It has protested strongly against its treatment by
German authorities, comparing it to that imposed by Nazis on Jews.
</P>
<P>
Scientology supporters today lodged protest in Bonn and other
German cities. The organization also vowed to resort to legal
steps against the interior ministers' decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
