<HEADLINE> UK Government Threatens to Ban Beef Imports From EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Britain's new Labor government has
threatened to block beef imports from the other European Union
(EU) countries unless they agree to implement anti-BSE or mad cow
disease measures in their countries before July 22.
</P>
<P>
British Agriculture Minister Jack Cunningham reportedly said in
a written statement to parliament that the British government
would ban beef imports from the other EU countries, which do not
apply the same controls against the BSE as Britain.
</P>
<P>
"I would very much prefer to have Europe-wide regulations
enforced, but if agreement cannot be reached at the (EU) council
of agriculture ministers on that date (July 22), I will have to
act unilaterally," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is no game. This is no bluff. I am in earnest in making
this announcement. The draft orders are in my briefcase," he said.
"It is nothing to do with protectionism. It is based on very
important advice to safeguard public health."
</P>
<P>
The British minister explained, "I thought it was an absurd
situation, with all the rigorous controls on beef in this country,
we are importing beef not subject to the same safeguards."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, EU Commission officials reportedly said today that
if Britain acted on its own, it would be illegal.
</P>
<P>
Gerry Kiely, spokesman for EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz
Fischler, said in Brussels today, "As in all cases where a
government does something which is not in conformity with EU law,
you start out with infringement procedures and possibly end up in
the Court of Justice." 
</P>
</TEXT>
