<DOCNO> XIE19970607.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Unemployment Rate Down to 4.8 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The unemployment rate in the
U.S. was down further in May to 4.8 percent, resulting from the
second-longest peacetime economic expansion in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Labor Department said today that payrolls rose by
138,000 jobs, the smallest increase in eight months. However, that
followed a huge 323,000 gain in April, the largest in 14 months.
The figure in April was revised up from a previous estimate of
just 142,000.
</P>
<P>
Much of the May job gains came in services. Construction
employment also rose by 23,000 jobs after declining in April. But
construction gains in the first five months of the year averaged
slightly below the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The number of factory jobs was largely unchanged over the past
two months, slipping by 5,000 after gaining 2,000 in April.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that the jobless rate was 3.8 percent for
adult men and 4.5 percent for adult women. For all Blacks, the
rate was 10.3 percent and for Hispanics, 7.4 percent. But for
Black male teens, it was as high as 32.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. jobless rate, which began the year at a seasonally
adjusted 5.4 percent, has declined for four months in a row. It's
now the lowest since November 1973, when Richard Nixon was
president.
</P>
<P>
Today's report also showed a 4-cent increase in workers'
average hourly earnings to 12.19 dollars, 3.8 percent higher than
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Noting the six years of growth, U.S. President Bill Clinton
welcomed the report as an endorsement of his policies.
</P>
<P>
"The American economy has now added 12.3 million new jobs since
I took office, and unemployment has now been below 6 percent for
almost three years," Clinton said in a statement today. "America's
economy is the strongest it has been in a generation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
