<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti MP, Wife Shot on Way Back Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A Kuwaiti parliamentary
member and his wife were shot by an unknown gunman today while
they were driving back home in the southern outskirts of Kuwait
city, but they escaped the assassination, Kuwait News Agency
(Kuna) reported.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah Al-Neibari was hit twice with one bullet on his
right shoulder and the other on the lower jaw and his wife was
also hit on her shoulder.
</P>
<P>
They were immediately rushed by a private car to Al-Adan
hospital to the south of Kuwait city where medical sources said
their conditions were stable.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time a gun shooting incident occurred in
Kuwait this year. On April 9, a 15-year-old student shot twice
and seriously injured his science teacher Mutaz Mahmoud Ibrahim,
35, in Asmaei Secondary School campus for failing him in
geology.
</P>
<P>
The reason of the gunman's attempt to kill the parliamentary
member is still unknown.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti acting Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh
Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah, who rushed to the hospital after he was
informed about the assassination bid, said the attack
"constitutes a discord which doesn't target a specific person or
some people, but all Kuwaiti people and the state of Kuwait."
</P>
<P>
"I was shocked when I heard the news," he said, adding that "I
hope the Ministry of Interior will stop those who try to incite
this discord and unveil their identities."
</P>
<P>
On whether this assassination attempt was linked to organized
crime, the minister said "I assure you it is a discord targeting
the Kuwaiti people."
</P>
<P>
Many Kuwaitis have been keeping firearms and explosives left
over after the Gulf War in 1991, although government authorities
repeatedly urged people who still keep illegal weapons to
hand them over. 
</P>
</TEXT>
