<HEADLINE> Int'l Agreements Implemented in HK May Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador Wang
Xuexian today sent notices to UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan that
14 international conventions, to which China is not a party but
which are implemented in Hong Kong, may continue to be implemented
in Hong Kong arter July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Wang, acting permanent representative of China to the UN, said
in the notices that Hong Kong will enjoy a high degree of
autonomy, except in foreign and defense affairs, after China
resumes the exercise of sovereignty from July 1, 1997 in
accordance with the Sino-British Joint Declaration signed on
December 19, 1984.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said that today's notices cover the first
batch of international conventions which China has not
participated in but are implemented in Hong Kong and these accords
may continue to be implemented. Chinese diplomats were working
hard to prepare documents on other conventions that will apply to
Hong Kong after its return to China.
</P>
<P>
The 14 conventions covered by today's notices are as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- the International Convention relating to the Simplification
of Customs Formalities of 3 November 1923 and the Protocol to the
said Convention of the same date;
</P>
<P>
-- the Agreement on the Importation of Educational, Scientific
and Cultural Materials of 22 November 1950;
</P>
<P>
-- the International Convention to Facilitate the Importation
of Commercial Samples and Advertising Materials of 7 November
1952;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention Concerning Customs Facilities for Touring of
4 June 1954 and the Additional Protocol to the Convention
concerning Customs Facilities for Touring, relating to the
Importation of Tourist Publicity Documents and Materials;
</P>
<P>
-- the Customs Convention on the Temporary Importation for
Private Road Vehicles of 4 June 1954;
</P>
<P>
-- the Customs Convention on the Temporary Importation for
Private Use of Aircraft and Pleasure Coats of 18 May 1956;
</P>
<P>
-- the Customs Convention on the Temporary Importation of
Commercial Road Vehicles;
</P>
<P>
-- the European Convention on Customs Treatment of Pallets Used
in International Transport;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention and Statute on Freedom of Transit of 20 April
1921;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention and Statute on the Regime of Navigable
Waterways of International Concern of 20 April 1921;
</P>
<P>
-- the Declaration Recognizing the Right to a Flag of States
Having no Sea-coast of 20 April 1921;
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention and Statute on the International Regime of
Maritime Ports of 9 December 1921;
</P>
<P>
-- the Amendment to the Montreal Protocol on Substances that
Deplete the Ozone Layer adopted at Copenhagen on 25 November 1992;
and
</P>
<P>
-- the Convention on Road Traffic of 19 September 1949.
</P>
</TEXT>
