<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Russian Reform with $884.6 Mln Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today announced
the approval of six loans totaling 884.6 million U.S. dollars to
back Russia's ambitious reform program.
</P>
<P>
The loans will be used as a first step to help strengthen
economic stability and foster improvements in education, health,
economic analysis, enterprise restructuring and the wholesale
electricity market.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's funding includes a 600 million dollar loan for
structural adjustment, which will help the government focus on a
range of sectoral reforms to promote renewed economic growth while
maintaining economic stability.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a 71 million dollar loan is earmarked for an
education innovation project, 66 million dollars for a health
reform pilot project, 22.6 million dollars for a bureau of
economic analysis project, 85 million dollars for an enterprise
restructuring services project and 40 million dollars for a
electricity sector support project.
</P>
<P>
Since Russia joined the World Bank in June 1992, the Bank's
commitments total approximately 7.5 billion dollars for 36
projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
