<HEADLINE> Final Results of 1997 Legislative Elections in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YOUNDE, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Cameroun's Supreme Court
proclaimed here today the results of the May 17 legislative
elections in Cameroun.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Cameroun People's Democratic Movement (CPDM) enjoys
an absolute majority with 109 seats out of 180 in the new
assembly.
</P>
<P>
The new assembly will comprise of seven parties as against
four in the last assembly. Apart from the CPDM, the Social
Democratic Front obtains 43, the National Union for Democracy and
Progress 13, the Union for Democracy and Change 5, the Movement
for Democracy and the Republic 1, the Union for the People of
Cameroun 1 and the Liberty Movement for Camerounian Youth 1.
</P>
<P>
Elections in three constituencies with 7 seats were cancelled
on June 4, 1997 by the supreme court. The re-run in the three
constituencies will be conducted within 30 days from the date of
cancellation.
</P>
<P>
The legislative elections were held in Cameroun on May 17,
1997. About 3.7 million voters cast their vote. About 1,000
candidates representing 45 political parties were vying for the
180 seats in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The first legislative elections in Cameroun were held in 1992.

