<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment Contributing to China's Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Overseas-funded enterprises'
supplementary role in China's economy has become one of the major
factors in the country's economic movement over the past 18 years.
</P>
<P>
This is manifested in their output, foreign trade volume, and
profit figures, according to Liu Zuozhang, deputy director of
Foreign Investment Management Department of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation Ministry, who spoke at the ongoing 2nd APEC
Exposition herein Yantai, a port city in Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of overseas-funded enterprises' industrial output to
China's total went up from 2.1 percent in 1990 to 7.2 percent in
1995, Liu said, and overseas-funded enterprises' foreign trade,
which grew 25 percent last year from the previous year, accounted
for 47 percent of China's total.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, China had approved more than 280,000
overseas-funded enterprises, involving a total contractual
investment of more than 469 billion US dollars, and more than
176.5 billion US dollars have actually been used, he added.
</P>
<P>
In the 1991-1995 period, overseas investment accounted for 11.8
percent of China's fixed assets and that figure went to 13 percent
last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
