<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: HKSAR PLC's 10th Meeting Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HASAR) ended its 10th plenary meeting here today with passage of
a package of bills.
</P>
<P>
It is significant that this was the second bill package adopted
by the 60-member legislature since it was elected last December.
On May 10, the PLC had passed the Holidays (1997 and 1998) Bill,
the first draft legislation tabled to the legislature.
</P>
<P>
The just-ended meeting reflects the PLC's fruitful work in
preparing the legislation before the July 1 handover.
</P>
<P>
The four bills which the PLC members passed at the third
reading in this South China city this morning are the Urban
Council (Amendment) Bill 1997, the Regional Council (Amendment)
Bill 1997, the District Board (Amendment) Bill 1997 and the
Legislative Council Commission (Amendment) Bill 1997.
</P>
<P>
The first three bills of the second package are designed to
seek to establish the Provisional Urban Council, the Provisional
Regional Council and Provisional District Boards for the
transitional period between July 1, 1997 and a date not later than
December 31, 1999, in order to fill a vacuum in the district
organizations as the existing Urban Council, Regional Council and
District Boards cease to function on June 30, 1997, a PLC source
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Under the bills, the Provisional Urban Council and the
Provisional Regional Council will each consist of not more than 50
members to be appointed by the Chief Executive of the HKSAR, and
each of the Provisional District Boards will be composed of not
more than 40 members also to be appointed by the Chief Executive.
</P>
<P>
The provisional district organizations will therefore operate
with the same statutory powers, functions and framework, and adopt
the same procedures of deliberation and modus operandi as their
predecessors, the source added.
</P>
<P>
The fourth bill of the passed second package, the Legislative
Council Commission (Amendment) Bill, aims to facilitate
administrative support to the legislature of the HKSAR after June
30, according to Michael Suen, secretary for policy coordination
of the Chief Executive's Office of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
He told the lawmakers here today that "the purpose of the bill
is to implement the recommendations of the Working Group on
Administrative Matters of the PLC to enable the continuing
application of the ordinance after June 30, and to make
transitional arrangements arising from the establishment of the
PLC and its supporting structure.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting also proceeded with the first and second
readings of the Immigration (Amendment) (N0.3) Bill 1997, the Hong
Kong Court of Final Appeal (Amendment) Bill 1997 and the Judicial
Service Commission (Amendment) Bill 1997, and decided to adjourn
the debate on the three bills for further scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
Miss Elsie Leung, secretary of justice of the future HKSAR,
expressed the hope that the PLC members can pass the three bills
before the July 1 handover.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the lawmakers at the meeting about the amendment
immigration bill, Miss Leung said "the bill seeks to provide for
the status of the permanent resident together with the right of
abode in the HKSAR."
</P>
<P>
According to Miss Leung, the bill seeks to provide for: the
various categories of the permanent resident of the HKSAR and the
procedure of implementation; the circumstances in which the right
of abode may be lost and the right to land in HK after the loss of
such right; the transitional arrangements for those who are not of
Chinese nationality but are permanent residents of HK before its
handover; and the definitions or their amendments of certain
expressions in the bill.
</P>
<P>
Article 24 of the Basic Law stipulates that there are six
categories of permanent residents who have the right of abode in
the HKSAR, Miss Leung said.
</P>
<P>
"I firmly believe that there is a pressing need to have the
bill enacted before July 1, 1997 by the PLC after examination,"
she said, noting that the bill on the right of abode, which is an
important task of the HKSAR, affects practically each and every
resident in the HKSAR. "Early legislation can ally people's
concern," she added.
</P>
<P>
As to the Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal (Amendment) Bill
1997, Miss Leung said the main purpose of moving the bill is to
include the provision of Article 90 in the Hong Kong Court of
Final Appeal Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
According to the article, the Chief Justice of the Court of
Final Appeal and the Chief Judge of the High Court of the HKSAR
shall be Chinese citizens who are permanent residents of the
region with no right of abode in any foreign country.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the Judicial Service Commission (Amendment) Bill
1997, Miss Leung told the lawmakers that the purpose of the bill
is to ensure that the first party of judges of the HKSAR is
smoothly named.
</P>
<P>
During today's meeting, the lawmakers also resumed the debate
on a motion on the Transitional Budget for 1997-1998, which was
moved by the Chief Executive's Office in early May. The PLC
finally gave its support to the Transitional Budget for 1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
Most of the legislators noted in their speeches that the
transitional budget fully accords with the established principles
of financial prudence and the relevant provisions in the Basic
Law, and seeks to ensure that on its establishment, the HKSAR
government has healthy fiscal reserves to meet the needs for
medium- and long-term development.
</P>
<P>
The PLC's House Committee opened its eighth session here this
afternoon after the one-day plenary meeting of the PLC closed its
doors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
