<HEADLINE> Damascus Declaration Members to Hold Ministerial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Damascus Declaration signatory
states' foreign ministers will meet in the Syrian capital late
this month to discuss the Mideast peace process, the Egyptian MENA
news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Top diplomats from Egypt, Syria and the six Gulf states --
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Bahrain and
Oman-- will attend the two-day meeting, said Issa Darwish, Syria's
Ambassador and Permanent Delegate to the Arab League.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk Shara will chair the meeting, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers will evaluate the latest developments on
Arab, regional and international arenas, work to coordinate
stances for pushing forward the peace process and boost relations
between the Arab countries in various fields, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting is of special importance due to the latest
developments in the Mideast peace process," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Mideast peace process collapsed in March when Israel began
construction of a new Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
At their previous meeting held here last December, foreign
ministers of the Damascus group approved a resolution on a joint
Arab political, security and economic agenda.
</P>
<P>
The eight-member alliance, formed in the Syrian capital in 1991
following the Gulf War, calls for joint security and military
arrangements in addition to economic cooperation among the eight
signatories. 
</P>
