<HEADLINE> Increase In Charitable Activities In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Charities have developed rapidly
since the Shanghai Charity Foundation was set up in May of 1994.
</P>
<P>
The foundation now has more than 110 million yuan in
donations, 60 percent of that from abroad, and has used 45 million
yuan to help 25,000 poor families.
</P>
<P>
The figures come from the foundation's Board of Directors'
sixth conference, which opened here today. It is the first
non-governmental charitable organization in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The foundation financed the Zhongren Recreation Home for the
Elderly, which was completed in October of 1996, and the Zhongren
Apartment Building for the Elderly, scheduled for completion in
1998.
</P>
<P>
It has also helped 1,020 elderly to marry, provided fellowships
or free lunches to over 3,500 students from poor families, opened
training courses for over 7,000 handicapped and jobless people,
and assisted poor families. About 25,000 households have received
assistance from the charitable organization in various ways.
</P>
<P>
Addressing today's meeting, Shi Derong, the organization's
secretary general, said that his foundation will try to get more
donations. This year it has planned a "Charity Day", "Street
Collection of 10,000 Donations", and has put collection boxes in
major department stores and hotels. It also plans to train 5,000
factory workers who are out of work, some of whom will be backed
in starting their own businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
