<HEADLINE> China Promises to Open Foreign Trade Wider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- China will open its domestic market
further to other countries by gradually lowering its tariffs to 15
percent, a rate compatible to that of a developing country, said
Wang Zixian, an official with the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (Moftec), here today.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
Exposition in this port city in Shandong Province, where he
promised to give foreigners greater room in China's foreign trade
within three years following China's joining the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China will have active economic cooperation with
other members of APEC and will contribute to building open and
fair world trade.
</P>
<P>
Wang estimates that China's foreign trade volume will reach 400
billion US dollars by the year 2000 and 800 billion US dollars by
2010, with imports and exports to be evenly weighted.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China's total foreign trade volume stood at 289.9
billion US dollars worth, with exports accounting for 151 billion
US dollars worth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
