<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Afghan Situation Takes Dramatic Turns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Since middle of May, the
situation in northern Afghanistan has taken a few dramatic turns
like a Hollywood action suspense movie.
</P>
<P>
What looked like a swift-paced end-game in the protracted
Afghan civil war has thus fallen into a see-saw pattern of
military engagement between the Afghan Islamic Taliban militia and
its rivals in the north.
</P>
<P>
The drama began on May 19 when General Abdul Malik,
second-in-command of Uzbek warlord Rashid Dostum, ousted his boss
in an unexpected coup and switched his support to the Taliban,
which enabled the Islamic militia to make a breakthrough in the
opposition-controlled north.
</P>
<P>
Buoyed by their landmark victory, the Taliban, who entered on
May 25 the historic city of Mazar-e-Sharif, Dostum's headquarters,
have once claimed that they would complete "in days" their
three-year campaign to take over the whole country.
</P>
<P>
Yet the euphoria created by the rout of Dostum, who is now in
Turkey, has turned into a nightmare for the Taliban as Malik
performed another about-face shortly after the capture of
Mazar-e-Sharif by his forces together with Taliban fighters.
</P>
<P>
When asked to disarm his forces by the Taliban, Malik quickly
broke rank with the Islamic militia just four days after Dostum's
flight and chased them out of Mazar-e-Sharif following a 15-hour
fighting, leaving some 300 Taliban fighters killed and over 1,000
including Taliban's foreign minister Mullah Ghaus captured.
</P>
<P>
As fighting spread across the north, the Taliban suffered their
worst defeat since they emerged from southern Afghanistan 30
months ago while Malik's troops retook four northern provinces of
Takhar, Faryab, Jozjan and Sar-e-Pol which the Taliban have
occupied for less than a week.
</P>
<P>
In the south, Tajik warlord and ousted military chief Ahmad
Masood has lost no time in launching an offensive against the
Taliban north of Kabul along the Salang highway which links
northern and southern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Quite a few strategic points and towns at the mouth of the
Panjshir valley, stronghold of Masood, and elsewhere have
meanwhile changed hands -- captured, recaptured and lost again -
between the Taliban and their opponents. As a result, a large
force of Taliban traveling north have been trapped, cut-off and
completely surrounded by opposition forces.
</P>
<P>
The escalation of fighting in northern Afghanistan has drawn
serious attention of the world community. Norbert Holl, the United
Nations special envoy to Afghanistan, who flew to Kabul at the end
of last month, has started a new round of shuttling diplomacy to
call on all the warring parties to solve the current critical
situation through negotiations and not by fighting.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan, a country composed of multiethnic groups, cannot
function smoothly under the complete domination of one particular
group even though it might be militarily the strongest, Holl said
in an interview at his office just one day before his departure
for Kabul last week.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic changes in northern Afghanistan have proved once
again that the only solution to the protracted Afghan conflict is
to form a broad-based government as envisaged by the UN, Holl
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
