<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Photo Exhibition In Fuzhou Highlights Patriotism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition entitled "Lin Zexu and
the Opium War" opened today in Fuzhou, the capital of Fujian
province in southeast China.
</P>
<P>
On display are 270 photos in three parts: patriotism and
safeguarding people, burning opium in Humen Town, and Hong Kong's
return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The first part is about the life and achievements of Lin Zexu,
the first national hero to fight foreign invaders in modern
Chinese history. The second is about the Opium War, which ended in
the signing of the "Nanjing Treaty", where the Qing dynasty ceded
Hong Kong to the British. The third concerns the 100-year history
of Hong Kong and the signing of the Sino-British Joint Declaration.
</P>
<P>
The week-long exhibition is sponsored by the Cultural Bureau of
Fuzhou, the Lin Zexu Foundation, and the Education Committee of
Fuzhou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
