<HEADLINE> URGENT: Taliban Recapture Strategic Town North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Islamic Taliban
militia today recaptured a strategic town north of Kabul from the
opposing factions after four hours of heavy fighting, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 Taliban fighters, under the cover of helicopter
gunships, took Jabul Siraj, about 77 kilometers north of Kabul,
from forces loyal to ousted Afghan military chief Ahmad Masood,
said Afghan sources in Peshawar, Pakistan's northwestern city.
</P>
<P>
The sources quoted the Taliban spokesman in Afghanistan's
southeastern city of Kandahar as saying the Islamic militia were
heading toward the Panjshir Valley, Masood's stronghold.
</P>
<P>
There is also fierce fighting in the area around Gulbahar,
about 80 kilometers north of Kabul, between Taliban and Masood
forces, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Jabul Siraj and Gulbahar, which are located at the mouth of the
Panjshir Valley, fell to Masood's hands on May 30.  
</P>
