<HEADLINE> Palestinian, Israeli Experts Meet in Cairo Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A Palestinian-Israeli expert meeting
will be held here tomorrow to tackle the Jewish settlements and
other important issues on the Mideast peace process, Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said today.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will attend the meeting as an observer, said Moussa
following a meeting between Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak here
this morning.
</P>
<P>
But the Egyptian top diplomat refused to describe such a drive
as positive or otherwise, saying it is necessary to wait and see
what tomorrow's meeting will lead to.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks broke down in March when
Israel began construction of a new Jewish settlement in disputed
Arab East Jerusalem. Palestinians conditioned the resumption of
negotiations on a halt to the settlement.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was decided upon after Arafat meeting Friday a
advisor to Israeli Prime Minister Binjamin Netanyahu who conveyed
some Israeli ideas to bring closer views between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that no comments should be made before tomorrow's
meeting," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He also declined to comment on Netanyahu's plan for the final
settlement with Palestinians, only saying that "he (Mr. Netanyahu)
spoke about the issue of Jeursalem before."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu' plan, which was revealed early this week, includes a
partial Israeli withdrawal from 40 percent of the West Bank and
strengthening the Israeli presence in Jerusalem and the Jewish
settlement in the West Bank. The Palestinians have rejected it.
</P>
<P>
Instead of fresh U.S. suggestions to bring closer Palestinian
and Israeli view points, Moussa said there are only Israeli
proposals now.
</P>
<P>
"We should not delve into the details of those proposals
because only the Palestinians have the right to do so," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has taken a central role in mediating an end to the
crisis between the Palestinians and Israelis after U.S. Mideast
coordinator Dennis Ross's shuttle trips tappered off.
</P>
<P>
While pessimistic that tomorrow's meeting would be a step
towards a summit between Netanyahu and Arafat, Moussa voiced hope
it would be "beneficial to the Palestinian issue."
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said Egypt and the Palestinians were working
on a five-point plan which includes a freeze on any change in the
status of Jerusalem and a ban on Jewish settlement of the West
Bank for a "sufficient period" of time.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, Israel should start at once the final phase
negotiations and fully implement the Hebron agreement, including
further troop withdrawal from the West Bank, operating Gaza
airport, starting Gaza port construction and opening the safe
passage between the West bank and the Gaza strip.
</P>
<P>
In return, the Palestinians would give a firm commitment to
address Israel's security demands, they added.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Egyptian efforts, the gap remained wide, especially
on the question of Jewish settlement, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has refused to stop the new construction and instead
proposed building a neighborhood for Arabs near the Jewish housing
project. He also proposed measures to ease the limitations against
the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
