<HEADLINE> Arafat Winds Up Brief Visit to Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Authority President
Yasser Arafat left here at noon after his second visit here in
four days to discuss Egypt's mediation efforts to move forward the
deadlocked Palestinian-Israeli talks.
</P>
<P>
The tete-a-tete between Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
Arafat later turned into an enlarged session that included
Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri, Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa, PA Minister of Local Administration Saeb Erekat, Arafat's
top advisors.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's several-hour visit came as Egypt's recent peace moves
seemingly stand a chance of reviving the peace process that
paralyzed in March when Israel broke ground for a new Jewish
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Today's discussions would mainly focus on the lastest proposals
to break the peace stalemate, said Moussa on the eve of the
talks. Both sides are yet to give remarks after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said Egypt and the Palestinians were working
on a five-point plan which includes a freeze on any change in the
status of Jerusalem and a ban on Jewish settlement of the West
Bank for a "sufficient period" of time.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, Israel should start at once the final
phase negotiations and fully implement the Hebron agreement,
including further troop withdrawal from the West Bank, operating
Gaza airport, starting Gaza port construction and opening the safe
passage between the West bank and the Gaza strip.
</P>
<P>
In return, the Palestinians would give a firm commitment to
address Israel's security demands, they added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leadership, at a weekly meeting chaired by
Arafat in Gaza Friday night, approved convocation of
Palestinian-Israeli-Egyptian ministerial meeting in Cairo to
examine the peace-making efforts.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have refused to return to the negotiating
table in the two-month-old Mideast peace crisis and made the
resumption of talks conditional on a halt of Israel's expansionary
policy.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who has played a central role in bridging the
differences between the two sides after the failed U.S. attempt,
reportedly had proposed a six-month freeze to Har Homa, the new
settlement project in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
But the sources said despite the Egyptian efforts, the gap
remained wide, especially on the question of Jewish settlement.
</P>
<P>
After his talks here, Arafat was expected to go to the
Jordanian capital of Amman for talks with King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's tour of Egypt and Jordan, the only two Arab countries
that signed peace deals with the Jewish state, also focuses on a
peace plan drafted by Israel's Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The plan, revealed by a cabinet source earlier this week,
includes a partial Israeli withdrawal from 40 percent of the West
Bank and strengthening the Israeli presence in Jerusalem and the
Jewish settlement in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians rejected the plan, with Arafat branding it as
"a violation for the peace process and the accords signed."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has refused to stop the new construction and instead
proposed building a neighborhood for Arabs near the Jewish housing
project. He also proposed measures to ease the limitations against
the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
