<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Amendment Immigration Bill Tabled to PLC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the Hong Kong
 Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) tabled an amendment
immigration bill here today to the Provisional Legislative Council
(PLC) for the first and second readings.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the Immigration (Amendment) (No.3) Bill 1997, HKSAR
Secretary of Justice Elsie Leung told PLC members this morning in
the South China city that she moved that the bill be read a second
time.
</P>
<P>
"The bill seeks to provide for the status of a permanent
resident together with the right of abode in the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region" in accordance with Article 24 of the Basic
Law, Leung said.
</P>
<P>
In drafting the bill, she said, "we have taken account of the
detailed arrangements set out in the decision of the Preparatory
Committee of the HKSAR made in July 1996 on the definition of Hong
Kong Permanent Citizens. It has also taken into account those
issues agreed upon in the (Sino-British) Joint Liaison Group," a
spokesman for the HKSAR Chief Executive's Office said in Hong Kong
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, Leung told the lawmakers, there are six
categories of permanent residents with the right of abode in the
HKSAR. According to Leung, they are as follows:
</P>
<P>
(1). Chinese citizens born in Hong Kong before or after the
establishment of the HKSAR;
</P>
<P>
(2). Chinese citizens who have ordinarily resided in Hong Kong
for a continuous period of not less than seven years before or
after the establishment of the HKSAR;
</P>
<P>
(3). Persons of Chinese nationality born outside Hong Kong of
those residents listed in categories (1) and (2);
</P>
<P>
(4). Persons not of Chinese nationality who have entered Hong
Kong with valid travel documents, have ordinarily resided in Hong
Kong for a continuous period of not less than seven years and have
taken Hong Kong as their place of permanent residence before or
after the establishment of the HKSAR;
</P>
<P>
(5). Persons under 21 years of age born in Hong Kong of those
residents listed in category (4) before or after the establishment
of the HKSAR;
</P>
<P>
(6). Persons other than those residents listed in categories
(1) to (5), who, before the establishment of the HKSAR, had the
right of abode in Hong Kong only.
</P>
<P>
According to Leung, the bill includes four major parts: to
provide for the various categories of permanent residents of the
HKSAR and the procedure of implementation; to provide for the
circumstances in which the right of abode may be lost and the
right to land in Hong Kong after the loss of such right; to
provide for the transitional arrangements for those who are not of
Chinese nationality but are permanent residents of Hong Kong
before its handover; and to provide for the definitions (or their
amendments) of certain expressions in the bill.
</P>
<P>
The bill does not provide for those who claim to enjoy the
right of abode in the HKSAR but have entered or sought to enter
Hong Kong unlawfully, she said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the issue, which has been a matter of public
concern, as "complex," Leung said a special task force set up
under the auspices of the Chief Executive's Office has now
undertaken to examine the issue and may soon make recommendations
on the ways to tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
"An early legislation can allay people's concern," she pointed
out, adding that the Basic Law only is the basic principles and
policies and it must be implemented by detailed articles of the
HKSAR laws.
</P>
<P>
Leung stressed that "there is a pressing need" for the
lawmakers to have the bill enacted before the July 1 handover and
the legislation on the right of abode is "an important task" of
the HKSAR.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970607.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal Bill Tabled at Provisional Legislature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Court of Final
Appeal (Amendment) Bill 1997 was tabled here today at the
Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) for scrutiny by the Chief
Executive's Office of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
The bill was moved for the first and second readings today at
the 10th plenary meeting of the post-handover legislature which
was meeting in Shenzhen, the Chinese city bordering Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Elsie Leung Oi-sie, Secretary of Justice of the HKSAR, told the
PLC members that the main purpose of moving the bill was to
include the provision of Article 90 of the Basic Law in the Hong
Kong Court of Final Appeal Ordinance enacted in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The essence of Article 90 is missing from that Ordinance,"
said Leung. The Article provides that the Chief Justice of the
Court of Final Appeal and the Chief Judge of the High Court of the
HKSAR shall be Chinese citizens who are permanent residents of the
Region with no right of abode in any foreign country.
</P>
<P>
Article 90 also mandates that in the case of appointment or
removal of judges of the Court of Final Appeal and the Chief Judge
of the High Court of the HKSAR, the Chief Executive shall obtain
the endorsement of the Legislative Council and report such
appointment and removal to the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress for record.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR's Secretary of Justice explained that in the Basic
Law, the constitutional document of Hong Kong after July 1, 1997,
Articles 88 to 90 contain provisions on the appointment of Judges
of the Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal.
</P>
<P>
"The substance of Article 88 and 89 have already been reflected
in the relevant provisions of the Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal
Ordinance enacted in 1995," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
