<DOCNO> XIE19970607.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judicial Service Commission Bill Tabled at Provisional Legislature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Judicial Service Commission
(Amendment) Bill 1997 was tabled here today at the Provisional
Legislative Council (PLC) for scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
Moved by the Chief Executive's Office of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR), the bill passed the first and
second readings at the 10th plenary meeting of the PLC here in
Shenzhen, the southern China city bordering Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Elsie Leung Oi-sie, Secretary of Justice of the HKSAR explained
to legislators that the main purpose of the bill was to ensure the
smooth appointment of the first group of judges of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
At the HKSAR government inauguration and swearing-in ceremony
on July 1, 1997, permanent Judges of the Court of Final Appeal and
Judges of the High Court should take their oaths immediately after
the Chief Executive, the principal officials, members of the
Executive Council and Members of the PLC, according to a decision
made last month by the Preparatory Committee for the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Leung stressed: "We support this decision. The swearing in of
the executive, the legislative and the judicial bodies on the same
occasion can signify the establishment en bloc of the HKSAR
government."
</P>
<P>
But legally speaking, members of the Judicial Officers
Recommendation Commission (JORC), an independent body formed under
the Basic Law to make recommendations to the Chief Executive on
the appointment of judges, should have taken their oaths before
making such recommendations.
</P>
<P>
"However, this arrangement is not possible on July 1, 1997,"
the Secretary of Justice told the PLC members.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, we propose that we should amend the law and add a
transitional provision to ensure that the recommendations made by
the JORC could not be challenged simply because its members have
not taken their oaths prior to making the recommendations," said
Leung.
</P>
<P>
She said that although the JORC Ordinance will not come into
force till July 1, 1997, the Chief Executive has already
appointed a JORC in order to make the necessary preparation for
the setting up of the Judiciary of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The JORC will officially be established on July 1, 1997, to
replace the existing Judicial Service Commission. Meanwhile, the
Judicial Service Commission Ordinance will also be re-titled the
Judicial Officers Recommendation Commission Ordinance on July 1,
said the Secretary of Justice.
</P>
<P>
The JORC has recommended to the Chief Executive that Andrew Li
Kwok-nang be the Chief Justice of the Court of Final Appeal. The
recommendation has gained wide support form PLC members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
