<HEADLINE> Two-time World Cup Winner Makes All-star Table Tennis Semis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Two-time World Cup winner Ma Wenge
crushed youngster Wang Liqin in straight sets to reach the
semi-finals of the China All-Star Table Tennis Tournament here on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Ma, who hasn't played competitive table tennis
for a month, put up a nearly perfect righthanded attacking game to
beat the teammate 10 years his junior, 21-15, 21-14, 21-14.
</P>
<P>
Ma, who has been among the world best for a decade but has
never won a world championship singles title, said he was
considering retirement.
</P>
<P>
"I feel wornout and want to call its quits," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang, tipped as China's best hope for his giant-killing run in
the last month's world championships, failed to find his form in
the game against the player he shared the same room with and has
beaten many times in training.
</P>
<P>
Wang, from Shanghai, had upset European stars Jean-Philippe
Saive, Carl Prean and Jorgen Persson and more favored Canadian
Johnny Huang in the world championships in Manchester, England,
before losing the semi-final to Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus.
</P>
<P>
World No. 3 and former world champion Kong Linghui also made
the last four after nipping Qin Zhijian in four sets.
</P>
<P>
Yang Ying, member of the reigning world champion team,
outlasted local favorite Zhu Fang in five sets to reach the
women's semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
Wang Chen, also from Beijing, came back from two sets down to
overcome Gong Yuechun 3-2 to reach the last four. 
</P>
</TEXT>
