<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Coupists Plead for Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The coupists that toppled Sierra
Leone's legitimate government led by President Tejan Kabbah
called on Friday for dialogue to end the crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here today, S. Koroma, the new
Chief of Army Defence Staff of the current military regime
appealed to the international community to employ diplomatic
option rather than force in restoring democracy in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
This has been seen as an apparent move of the coup leaders to
stave off imminent military offensive by West African Peacekeeing
Force known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
S.Koroma, reported to be elder brother of coup leader Johnny
Koroma, urged representatives from the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS), the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
and the United Nations to assess the situation in the capital
Freetown.
</P>
<P>
"Give us time, i mean find time to come to negotiate, but
definitely we oppose military intervention," S. Koroma was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he denied earlier reports that the military junta
offered to restore democracy in Sierra Leone in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
He said: "I did not say the military will have to stay in
power for 18 months. I just said that the people will have to
choose, especially the international community, between Tejan
Kabbah and peace. If you agree for Tejan Kabbah, i am sure peace
is not going to be in this country for 18 months."
</P>
<P>
The military leadership asked on Friday all workers in
government offices and agencies to return to work, but many
failed to oblige.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the workers were incensed about the massive
looting and mayhem that accompanied the May 25 coup and were
unsure of their safety.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people have been fleeing the tension and
insecurity in Freetown. Many set off on Friday at a tense feeling
of danger that ECOMOG bombardment might take place this weekend.
A BBC report said that over 80 people died in Sierra Leone when a
packed bus plunged into a river that day.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, sources in Nigeria said the Nigerian air force
airlifted on Thursday about 250 people, mostly Nigerians, who
were affected by the strife in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The returnees, most of them business people, were handed over
to "unprepared" officials of the National Emergency Relief
Agency, which later brought them to a camp in the outskirts of
Abuja, capital of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that officials of the camp have been working
hard to meet the needs of the returnees though they were not
informed about the airlift operation before.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian air force operation took place shortly before the
departure of the U.S. helicopter carrier Kearsarge from off
troubled Sierra Leone for the Mediterranean after evacuating
2,509 people, including 451 Americans.
</P>
<P>
To keep a close watch at the developments in Sierra Leone, the
United Nations has set up a coordinating unit in Conakry, Guinea.
It will also prepare an inter-agency assessment mission to
Freetown to check the huanitarian needs there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
