<HEADLINE> Indian PM Calls for Closer Regional Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister I. K.
Gujral today called on South Asian countries to work together to
tackle the region's common problems of slow growth and mass
poverty.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Nepal Council of World Affairs here today, the
visiting Indian prime minister said that his government is trying
to work out a South Asia policy based on cooperation, friendship
and goodwill.
</P>
<P>
As India will inevitably become part of the global economy, "we
realize that we can only move ahead hand in hand with our
immediate neighbors," Gujral said.
</P>
<P>
"The way forward for us is the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC)," he added, talking about the role of
the seven-nation grouping of Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka, which was established in
1985.
</P>
<P>
A new pattern of relationships has been built between India,
Nepal, Bangladesh, Bhutan and Sri Lanka last year, Gujral said,
referring to a sub-regional cooperation mechanism under the SAARC
umbrella.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the new South Asian spirit will also
prevail in India-Pakistan relations in the future.
</P>
<P>
"It is the time for Asian statesmanship to rise above petty
disputes and differences, to bury the divisive issues of the past,
and to embark on the new road to collective progress," Gujral told
the audience including diplomats, intellectuals and senior Nepali
government officials.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand was present at the
program organized by the Nepal Council of World Affairs, a
semi-governmental institute.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a joint press conference was held here today by the
two prime ministers before Gujral concludes his three-day visit to
Nepal.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, Gujral said that his current Nepal visit, the
first bilateral one after he became Indian prime minister in
April, underlined the emphasis of importance of the bilateral
relations between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Prime Minister Chand told the press conference that he
was satisfied with the official talks between him and Gujral on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that one important decision made during the talks was
the time-frame for addressing each of the bilateral issues between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"We deeply appreciate India's acceptance of the demand by Nepal
for a transit route to Bangladesh," Chand said.
</P>
<P>
The Indian prime minister on Friday agreed to provide an
alternative transit route through the narrow strip of the Indian
territory between Nepal and Bangladesh for Nepal's foreign trade
on the experimental basis.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to leave here for home later today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
