<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Urges Import Liberalization in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank, the largest donor
agency to Bangladesh, suggested that the government should
announce a medium-term strategy in its next budget for further
import liberalization.
</P>
<P>
In a recent report on trade policy reform, the bank recommended
that a three-rate schedule of 10, 20 and 35 percent needs to be
adopted in the next budget with zero rates only for imported
inputs for exporters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, low rates between zero and 20 percent should be
announced now for fiscal 1999-2000, the bank said, adding that a
maximum rate of 20 percent would retain some protection for
domestic industry against alleged foreign dumping.
</P>
<P>
Additional protection -- a 2.5-percent import permit fee, a
15-percent value-added tax on textiles and use of tariff values in
duty assessment -- should be removed to provide normal protection
by scheduled customs duties transparently.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank said that for an open and stable trade regime,
which attracts investors and stimulates export growth, the
government should take the program of import liberalization as top
priority in its strategy for trade reform.
</P>
<P>
Dispelling the fears of large revenue losses, the World Bank
said a cut in the import-weighted tariffs to half of their present
level could lead to an estimated 19 billion taka (about 475
million U.S. dollars) revenue loss, but it should be offset by
increased volume of imports.
</P>
<P>
It noted that bans on import of sugar, salt and some other
commodities are somewhat meaningless because large amounts of
these commodities are imported illegally from India.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a survey, the bank said illegal imports constitute
approximately 18 percent of total imports into Bangladesh.
Smuggling from India totals 519 million U.S. dollars against
Bangladesh's export of 126 million dollars to India.
</P>
<P>
Compared with other countries, Bangladesh has a long way to go
in its trade policy reforms, the bank report added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970607.0095 </DOCNO>
