<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: What Makes Thai Bourse Dip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Thailand
(SET) continued to sink these days, closing at an eight-year low
on Friday. The unchecked declining trend on the Thai bourse are
blurring the existing scene of the local financial sector and
causing more concern on how far it would go.
</P>
<P>
The broad-based SET index plunged 17.43 points to close at
530.62, the lowest since April 1989, amid heavy transactions with
declining issues outnumbering advancing ones 204 to 96. Analysts
said that the Thai government's tight baht policy may have fueled
the recent slump on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
The total trading value Friday nearly doubled to 5.2 billion
baht from Thursday's 2.8 billion baht, while the trading volume
soared to 170.8 million shares from Thursday's 98 million shares.
Dealers continued to sell even blue-chip shares to cashing in baht
to arbitrage on the 10 percent gap in the price of the baht
currency between the domestic and offshore markets.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector saw the highest trading volume on Friday as
foreign investors sold blue-chip banking issues to cash in the
baht because of the scarcity of the currency on the market.
</P>
<P>
The medium rate of the baht against the US dollar was fixed at
25.81 on the local market on Friday, around 10 percent more
expensive on offshore markets where the Thai central bank late May
engineered a shortage of the baht currency to deter speculators
betting on a devaluation.
</P>
<P>
The baht remained strong on Friday on offshore markets, traded
at 23.97/24.07 against the dollar after it jumped to a 13-year
high of 23.8/24 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The SET index has been edging down at a pace between 3.04 and
6.78 points a day over the past week after the Thai central bank's
policy was in place. On May 30, the last trading day of May, the
index perked at 566.35 points.
</P>
<P>
Reports that the Thai central bank's tight baht policy would
remain for three to six months on offshore trading also fed the
trend on the bourse, as it could slow capital inflow and cause
other problems on the market, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, worries about the level of the non-performing
loans in the country, which could bring about liquidity problems
in the banking system, might also be a contributor to the market
movement, as financial institutions is to disclose their
non-performing loans by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Most analysts said that foreigners are expected to continue to
sell stocks for the baht and the Thai bourse will remain under the
pressure next week. Some dealers said that the SET index could
expect a new technical resistance mark at 500.00 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
