<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Foreign Reserves Rise to 31 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's foreign exchange
reserves have recovered to the level of 30 billion U.S. dollars
thanks to the improved balance of payments, said the Bank of Korea.
</P>
<P>
At the end of May, foreign reserves reached 31.9 billion
dollars, up 2.07 billion from the end of April.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the trade balance, the stabilization of foreign
exchange rates also contributed to the sizable rise in the foreign
reserves, the central bank said in a latest report.
</P>
<P>
The slide of the value of won, the local currency, against
U.S. dollar continued from 840 to 1 in January to 890 to 1 in May
this year as the reserves dropped from 33.2 billion dollars last
December to 29.15 billion dollars at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
Beginning in April, however, the amount of the country's
foreign currency reserves rose.
</P>
<P>
As speculative demands for foreign exchange subsided, deposits
of foreign currencies among South Koreans also declined:
outstanding foreign exchange deposits stood at 2.37 billion
dollars at the end of May, down 930 million dollars from April.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Korea predicted that the upward trend of foreign
reserves will hold steady as the improvement of the trade balance
widens and the inflow of stock funds from foreign investors is
expected to rise.
</P>
<P>
The optimal level of a country's foreign reserves as
recommended by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) is an amount
equal to the total import value of three months. Based on the IMF
recommendation, South Korea's foreign reserves are still
considered insufficient as its imports are surpassing a monthly
average of 12 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970607.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Ivory Debate: to Trade or to Ban? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Wang Nengbiao)
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Convention on International Trade in
Endangered Species (CITES ) will start a 12-day meeting next Monday in
Harare, the capital of Zimbabwe, to decide the fate of African
elephants.
</P>
<P>
At this meeting, the CITES member countries will cast their votes on
whether to lift the eight-year old ivory trade ban or not.
</P>
<P>
Long before the meeting, campaigns for and against the
trade of ivory and other elephant products had already been launched.
Zimbabwe, Botswana and Namibia have been lobbying for the down-listing
of elephants from appendix i of the convention which entails a total
ban on ivory trade to appendix ii which will allow them to resume a
limited legal ivory trade. Some other African countries such as Kenya
and Zambia are firmly opposed to the down-listing.
</P>
<P>
The proponents argue that they have achieved success in protection
of elephants and the number of the animal has increased in their
countries.
</P>
<P>
They say that they need the resources to revamp their national
parks and promote their tourism as well as fight against poaching.
</P>
<P>
They also say the increasing number of elephants are threatening
vegetation, other species and even humen beings.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Mugabe said, "When culling operations and ivory trade
are stopped, the elephant herds get out of control and wreak havoc on
the lives and crop of our rural farmers adjacent to our game parks."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe even claimed that it is being unfairly punished by those
countries which fail to contain poaching and protect their elephants
effectively.
</P>
<P>
There are 580,000 elephants currently in Africa, of which
one-thirds are in Zimbabwe, Botswana and Namibia. The three also hold
a total of 100 tons ivory in government strongrooms.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe holds 65,000 elephants, which are far above that its range
can sustain. Ecologists said Zimbabwe can only sustain 35,000
elephants. If the limited trade is allowed, the country can sell its 40
tons of stockpiled ivory. In Botswana, elephant population is
increasing by five percent annually.
</P>
<P>
Opponents maintain that if ivory trade is allowed, whatever you do to
limit it, poaching will be promoted and become rampant and demand for
ivory supplies in the international market will increase.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Tourism Minister Amusaa Mwanamwambwa said that lifting the
ban will "open the floodgate to senseless elephant slaughter due to
the demand that this will create."
</P>
<P>
The opponents also say that raising funds through ivory trade to
protect elephants is the same as raising funds through drug sale to
fight against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
They say elephants are important tourism resources and the revenue
from elephant-based tourism will be much more than that from ivory
trade and killing elephants will bring heavy inflict on tourism.
</P>
<P>
Some international organizations related to wildlife protection are
also divided on the issue. The London-based environmental
Investigation Agency (EIA ) said in a document on the success of CITES
that the seriously declining elephant populations are slowly being
reversed and elephants are now returning to areas once believed to be
extinct.
</P>
<P>
But TRAFFIC, the world's largest wildlife trade monitoring
organization, has announced its support for the proposal by Botswana,
Namibia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
CITES imposed the ban on the ivory trade in 1989 in view of the
fast drop of the number of African elephants in 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The petition for the limite trade needs support of the two-thirds
of the 136 CITES member states to be approved.
</P>
<P>
The debate on the issue will be much fiercer at this meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
