<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Pays Lightning Visit to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Authority President
Yasser Arafat arrived here this morning for the second meeting in
four days with President Hosni Mubarak to discuss Egypt's recent
mediation efforts to move forward the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leadership, at a weekly meeting chaired by
Arafat in Gaza Friday night, approved convocation of
Palestinian-Israeli-Egyptian ministerial meeting in Cairo to
examine the peace-making efforts.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have refused to return to the negotiating
table in the two-month-old Mideast peace crisis and made the
resumption of talks conditional on a halt of Israel's expansionary
policy.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Friday that the two leaders'
talks will mainly focus on the lastest proposals to break the
stalled peace process that collapsed since March when Israel broke
ground for a new Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said Egypt and the Palestinians were working
on a five-point plan which includes a freeze on any change in the
status of Jerusalem and a ban on Jewish settlement of the West
Bank for a "sufficient period" of time.
</P>
<P>
The Mubarak-Arafat discussions today are expected to revolve
around the five main points in order to reach an agreement between
the two sides, they said.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, Israel should start at once the final phase
negotiations and fully implement the Hebron agreement, including
further troop withdrawal from the West Bank, operating Gaza
airport, starting Gaza port construction and opening the safe
passage between the West bank and the Gaza strip.
</P>
<P>
In return, the Palestinians would give a firm commitment to
address Israel's security demands, they added.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who has recently intensified efforts to bridge the
differences between the two sides, reportedly had proposed a
six-month freeze to Har Homa, the new settlement project in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
But the sources said despite the Egyptian efforts, the gap
between the two sides remained wide, especially on the question of
Jewish settlement.
</P>
<P>
After his talks here, the Palestinian leader is expected to go
to the Jordanian capital Amman for talks with King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's tour in Egypt and Jordan, the only two Arab countries
that signed peace deals with the Jewish state, would also discuss
a peace plan by Israel's Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The plan, revealed by a cabinet source earlier this week,
includes a partial Israeli withdrawal from 40 percent of the West
Bank and strengthening the Israeli presence in Jerusalem and the
Jewish settlement in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians rejected the plan and Arafat described it as "a
violation for the peace process and the accords signed."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has refused to stop the new construction and instead
proposed building a neighborhood for Arabs near the Jewish housing
project. He also proposed measures to ease the limitations against
the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
