<HEADLINE> Kenya Agrees to Pay Uganda Higher Electricity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has agreed to pay Uganda a
higher rate of electricity supplied by Uganda to Nairobi, reported
the local daily the New Vision today.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of the Uganda Electricity Board (UEB) led by
Managing Director Simon d'Ujanga left here for Nairobi yesterday
to sign agreements on the affair with Kenya Power and Lighting
Company.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreements, per unit of electricity supplied by
UEB to Nairobi has increased from 0.22 US cents in the 1950s to 8.5
US cents at present.
</P>
<P>
However, reliable sources here said that the Kenyan decision came
in the wake of increased pressure for tariff revision by President Y.
Museveni of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan decision followed a recent meeting between Museveni and
President Moi of Kenya at the OAU summit in Harare, Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements, Kenya will pay up to 8.5 cents for per unit
of power consumed between 5.00 a. m. and 6.00 p.m. The kenyans will
pay 6.5 cents for per unit of power consumed between 11.00 p.m. and
5.00 a.m. enditem

