<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 08:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Media Condemn Assassination of MP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's leading newspapers
today all condemned the assassination attempt on parliamentary
member Abuddullah Al-Neibari's life Friday in their front pages
and described the crime as an ugly act against the nation.
</P>
<P>
Neibari and his wife were driving home from their weekend
villa near the Saudi border Friday evening when the attack took
place. Eye witnesses said he was stopped by two cars while driving
on a side way to Kuwait city and the attackers sprayed his car
with machine-gun fire.
</P>
<P>
Neibari was hit twice with one bullet on his right shoulder and
the other on the lower jaw and his wife was also hit on her
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
They were immediately rushed by a private car to Al-Adan
hospital to the south of Kuwait city where medical sources said
their conditions were stable.
</P>
<P>
No one claimed responsibility for the attack; but unconfirmed
reports this morning said the suspects had been arrested.
</P>
<P>
Arabic daily Al-Qabas said the attack was aimed at "realizing
several targets at one time...it is an assassination against
democracy, the rule of institutions and public freedoms, if not to
say the assassination of a nation."
</P>
<P>
Another Arabic daily Al Watan said that "this criminal act
should be exploited to review the security situation in Kuwait
and particularly the crisis of the spread of weapons."
</P>
<P>
English daily Arab Times said "an iron fist is required
to grab hold of the country's affairs and strengthen
security."
</P>
<P>
Leaders of Kuwaiti government, parliament and other
governmental governmental organizations all strongly condemned the
crime. They said this was unprecedented in Kuwait's history.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti parliamentary Speaker Ahmad Al-Saadoun accused corrupt
people and thieves of public funds of being behind the
attack, adding that "this is a message to the Kuwaiti people
and to the honest."
</P>
<P>
Neibari, 61, won parliamentary elections in 1992 and 1996
and headed the parliamentary panel for protection of the
public funds. He is now a leading member in the Kuwaiti
Democratic Forum (liberals).
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti acting Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh
Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah who rushed to the hospital after he was
informed of the assassination said the attack "constitutes a
discord which doesn't target a specific person or some people,
but all Kuwaiti people and the state of Kuwait."
</P>
<P>
This was the second gun shooting incident in Kuwait this
year. A 15-year old student on April 9 shot twice and seriously
injured his science teacher Mutaz Mahmoud Ibrahim, 35, on Asmaei
Secondary School campus for failing him in geology.
</P>
<P>
Many Kuwaitis have been keeping firearms and explosives left
over after the Gulf War 1991, although governmental authorities
repeatedly urged the people to hand them over. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970607.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of crude
palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week mixed.
</P>
<P>
On the CPO physicals market this week, the price of June South
fell gradually from 1,277.50 ringgit (about 511 U.S. dollars) per
ton to 1,217.50 ringgit (about 487 U.S. dollars) per ton at the
week's close, against 1,275 ringgit (about 510 U.S. dollars) per
ton at last week's close.
</P>
<P>
Trade houses liquidated their positions and most players were
sidelined ahead of the summer holidays.
</P>
<P>
June South dipped as the market reacted to some bearish
forecast figures for the month of May, released by private
forecaster, Ivan Wong, who forecast a production figure of 784,000
tons, an increase of seven percent compared with April while the
stock figure was at 745,000 tons, an increase of about 50,000 tons
compared with the previous figure.
</P>
<P>
The bearish sentiment on the CPO physicals market is expected
to prolong as players would continue to liquidate their positions
next week, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
On the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM), the metal price during
the week fluctuated between 13.79 ringgit (about 5.516 U.S.
dollars) and 14.08 ringgit (about 5.632 U.S. dollars) per kg
before closing 10 sen better at 14.08 ringgit per kg.
</P>
<P>
Weekly turnover rose to 508 tons against 406 tons last week.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the week, the premium between the KLTM and that
of the London Metal Exchange (LME) narrowed to 85 U.S. dollars
against 135 U.S. dollars previously.
</P>
<P>
Tin price is expected to be volatile next week with the metal
hovering between 14.00 ringgit and 14.25 ringgit per kg, dealers
said, adding the KLTM's market direction will be dictated by the
uncertain movements on the LME, while demand for the metal is not
expected to be subdued.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian rubber market saw sentiment remain weak this week
although July RSS One gained half-a-sen to 284.00 sen (about 113.6
U.S. cents) per kg while SMR 20 fell three sen to close at 263.00
sen (about 105.2 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) daily
market indicator price for June 5 stood at 215.52
Malaysia/Singapore cents (sen) against 215.15 cents (sen) at the
end of last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average rose to 216.36 cents against 214.09
cents previously.
</P>
<P>
The market is expected to drift further next week due to poor
demand, lack of market moving factors and buyers reserve, dealers
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
