<HEADLINE> Pakistan Prime Minister for Better Indo-pak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said that both India and Pakistan should reduce their
defense budget by mutual agreement.
</P>
<P>
"But before that, we should try to generate confidence in each
other," he said in an interview given to an Indian TV channel,
which is to be broadcast on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that he was hopeful of "breaking of ice in the
bilateral relationship with India because of the positive attitude
of Indian Prime Minister I.K. Gujral."
</P>
<P>
He said that India and Pakistan must learn some lesson from the
50 years of confrontation and that temperature must be brought
down immediately. "This is not the time to fight. We must learn
from our past mistakes and should analyze what all we have gained
or lost. We fought wars and spent so much on defense budget
instead of concentrating on the development of both the nations.
We have only suffered by adopting a path of confrontation. It's
high time we should change our attitude," he further said.
</P>
<P>
"I want to discuss all the issues but it would be better if we
talk about Kashmir also. I have requested the Indian prime
minister that troops should be withdrawn from Kashmir as a first
gesture which will help in building the atmosphere of trust. I can
understand the limitations of Mr. Gujral, but I too have got my
own limitations. I found Mr. Gujral a very nice person and I hope
he will respond positively," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I want to go to India to watch cricket matches and I want
Gujral to come to Pakistan to watch cricket," Sharif added.
</P>
