<HEADLINE> Hyacinth Weed Has Economic Value: Prof. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A professor of agronomy in Kenya
has said that the water hyacinth, which now threatens Lake Victoria's
ecosystem, has economic value.
</P>
<P>
Eliud Omollo, a professor at the Egerton University,
said Friday that when dried, the hyacinth could be fed to
animals as its high protein content enabled the animals to
grow at a fast rate.
</P>
<P>
Students of agro-technology at the university are studying
how to use a large rake to clear the weed, dry it up and chop it
into small pieces to feed the animals like rabbits and pigs, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Researches from developed countries like Australia and Japan
have shown that the weed has other economic uses, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he advised the Kenyan government to encourage the
physical extraction of the weed to complement efforts of beetles
introduced in the lake, the second largest fresh water lake
in the world.
</P>
<P>
The insect could only contain the weed's spread rather than
eradicate it completely, he said.
</P>
<P>
About 60 million Neochetina beetles, a natural enemy of the
hyacinth, would be released in at least 150 stations on the
Kenyan side this year, making Kenya the first in east Africa to
advocate the use of beetles.
</P>
<P>
The hyacinth now covers an area of more than 70,000 hectares
of water in Kenyan parts of the lake.
</P>
<P>
The hyacinth, one of the fastest-spreading plants
on the earth, was first noticed in Lake Victoria in the 1980s, but
did not pose a significant problem until the 1990s. enditem

=06070810

=06070825
NNNN
16:14 16:14 g # PAB
