<HEADLINE> Former Australian Prime Minister Supports China's WTO Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation
(APEC) members should give their full support to China's accession
to the World Trade Organization (WTO) at the earliest possible
date, former Australian Prime Minister Bob Hawke said here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that China's accession to the WTO is in the interests
of the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at the second APEC exposition that opened in
this coastal city in east China on Friday.
</P>
<P>
He made the speech in response to the comment that China's
accession to the WTO will pose threat to the world.
</P>
<P>
Some persons' concern that China's rise to an economic power in
the first 25 years of the next century will pose a threat to the
world is groundless, he said.
</P>
<P>
He gives two reasons to support his view. First, he said that
people should not forget the country's history. China had
become powerful in the past 2,000 years, but it had never been
seeking hegemony in the world. Second, he believes that China
needs a peaceful environment to tackle the challenge of feeding
and keeping warm its population, which total 1.2 billion at
present.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the theory of "China threat" is absolutely
groundless, he said.  
</P>
