About 110 million people in more than 10 African countries
speak Kiswahili, he said at the opening of a two-day symposium
on Kiswahili language in Eldoret on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has a golden opportunity to develop the language because
over 80 percent of locals speak it, he added.
</P>
<P>
Africa depends on foreign languages for communication for many
years due to failure by Africans to develop a common and
indigenous language, he lamented.
</P>
<P>
Ipara Odeo, a lecturer at Moi University, also called on
Africans to invest in the development of the language, suggesting
that Kiswahili be adopted as a medium of instruction from primary
to university level. enditem

