<HEADLINE> Britain Assists Kenya's Tourism Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The British Tourist Authority
(BTA) is willing to share its experience with the Kenya Tourism
Board (KTB) to promote tourism of the two countries, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The BTA can help the KTB in research and other related
areas so that the newly-installed Kenyan body can benefit from
the 30-year experience of their British counterpart, said Robin
Young, a BTA manager for Africa, Asia-Pacific and Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The British government's decision to impose visa restrictions
on Kenyans has not affected the number of Kenyan visitors to
Britain, the reports quoted Young as saying at a workshop here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kenya ranks the third in Africa in the number of visitors to
Britain with South Africa the first, Young said.
</P>
<P>
As many as 56,000 Kenyans visited Britain last year and spent
almost 91 million U.S. Dollars there -- nearly 1,600 Dollars each
on the average. London was the most popular destination with the
biggest attractions for shopping and theater-going.
</P>
<P>
Britain earned 13 billion pounds (some 20.6 billion Dollars)
last year from 26 million visitors from all over the world.
</P>
