<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Smokers Increasing in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- More people are smoking and many of
them start at a younger age, today's "China Daily" quoted a latest
national survey as saying.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that about 590 million people in China, or half
the country's population, risk being harmed directly and passively
by cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
Some 37.6 percent of people aged 15 or so are now smoking
cigarettes, up 3.74 percentage points compared with 1984,
according to the survey which was conducted among 120,000 young
people aged 15 or older by the Chinese Academy of Preventive
Medicine and the Chinese Association for Smoking or Health.
</P>
<P>
Of cigarette smokers, 66.94 percent are male and 4.19 percent
are female. Based on the rates, the poll-takers estimate there
are 320 million smokers in China. There are more male smokers in
rural than urban areas, the survey reported. The proportion of
smokers among urban women is a bit higher than for rural women,
the survey reported.
</P>
<P>
Smokers usually begin lighting up at an average of 20, three
years earlier than in 1984. The number of young smokers has
increased by 9.66 percent among people between the ages of 15 to
19, and 36 percent for those between 25 to 29 and 43.6 percent for
those in the 40-44 age group. There are fewer smokers among
people above 45 years old.
</P>
<P>
Each smoker puffs an average of 15 cigarettes a day, two more
than 1984.
</P>
<P>
Chen Minzhang, Minister of Health, yesterday called upon all
Chinese to join the fight for a smoke-free society.
</P>
<P>
Chen added that China's anti-smoking campaign would get impetus
from the 10th World Conference on Tobacco or Health which is
scheduled to be held in Beijing in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
