<HEADLINE> King: Strong Economy Frees Malaysia From Outside </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's economic strength
has freed the nation from external pressures, Malaysian King
Tuanku Ja'afar said today.
</P>
<P>
The king was thankful for the rapid economic growth without
which he said Malaysia might not be able to enhance its image as a
developing nation and a respected Muslim country.
</P>
<P>
Over the past nine years, Malaysia achieved an average annual
growth rate of 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Malaysians should be thankful because a number of developing
countries, because of their weak economy, were still not free
economically and politically, he said at an investiture here in
conjunction with his 75th birthday today.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "The country must move forward with
excellence by ensuring that the generation we create will reject
any form of malpractice and corruption."
</P>
<P>
The king is confident that Malaysia has a strong foundation to
move forward into a developed nation with its own characteristics.
But he said achieving this depends much on the people upholding
noble values like being hardworking, disciplined, dedicated and
observing high ethics.
</P>
<P>
He urged Malaysians to master the computer and the multimedia
technology in order to fully benefit from the country's Multimedia
Super Corridor project, which is a 50 kilometer by 15 kilometer
zone south of here devoted to multimedia products and services.
</P>
<P>
The people could not avoid their lives from being influenced by
the information technology (IT), the king said, adding, "If no
effort is made to learn and master the computer, I'm afraid a
segment of the population will be left behind in this IT age."
</P>
