<HEADLINE> Hydropower Stations Threatened to Be Closed in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Two hydropower stations in northern
Vietnam are in danger of being shut down if no rain is expected in
the near future, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Water in the two reservoirs feeding the turbines are at a
record low following a prolonged hot and dry weather in northern
Vietnam since mid-May.
</P>
<P>
The water level was about 30 percent of that during the same
time last year, and engineers at the country's biggest hydropower
station were forced to limit the eight turbines supplying the
national grid to no more than three hours a day to meet peak
consumption.
</P>
<P>
The three existing thermal power plants have been running at
full capacity to meet demand.
</P>
<P>
The possible shortage of electricity in northern Vietnam
signals a severe shortage of electricity throughout the whole
country for the coming dry season and summer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
