<DOCNO> XIE19970607.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Calls for U.N. Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia has called for reforms in
the U.N. Security Council (UNSC) to make it more representative of
the composition of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"Reform is absolutely necessary to ensure that the actions
passed by the UNSC are supported by all members of the U.N.; after
all, all the UNSC's authority is based on the U.N. Charter and
acquired from all members of the U.N.," Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to officials of the Foreign Ministry, Alatas made the
remarks when launching the "Indonesia and the United Nations
Security Council 1995 and 1996" book.
</P>
<P>
"The UNSC needs to be open to transition, toward the creation
of a more secure, peaceful and humane world," Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was clear that the UNSC's authority, capability and
credibility very much depend on the perception, interests and
political will of UNSC permanent members.
</P>
<P>
"This requires all of us to think critically and to strive to
create a more democratic and more representative UNSC to better
mirror today's global reality," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The 200-page book published by the Permanent Mission of the
Republic of Indonesia to the United Nations, contains the views
and positions of Indonesia on issues discussed during its
membership in the UNSC, from January 1995 to December 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
