<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Internationalism From U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today urged the United States to follow the course of
internationalism in partnership with the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a commencement address at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, Annan pledged to graduating students "to
work indefatigably to anchor the United States firmly to the
course of internationalism."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. even now is debating its future role in the world
community, and the place of the U.N. within its overall foreign
policy vision, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his concerns over the erosion of Washington's
commitment to the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Annan urged to "continue the productive partnership between the
United States and the United Nations and go forward together with
a positive, can-do attitude to win the new peace and prosperity
that beckons."
</P>
<P>
Washington has failed to pay U.N. dues of more than one billion
U.S. dollars while the U.S. Congress demands more reforms of the
world body. 
</P>
</TEXT>
