<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Plans Panel to Watch Foreign Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Labor and Social Welfare
Ministry is planning to set up a high-level committee to protect
Thai employees from any mass layoffs by foreign companies, which
may flee Thailand when they face business problems, a local
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which will be chaired by a deputy prime
minister, will watch some 2,500 foreign businesses in Thailand as
the ministry predicted that a large number of workers would lose
their jobs this year due to tougher economic conditions, the
Bangkok Post said.
</P>
<P>
The proposed panel will be empowered to draw up rescue measures
for workers and enforce them on their foreign employers, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The committee will also be authorized to order state agencies
to take precautions to ensure that Thai workers are protected
under Thai law.
</P>
<P>
The formation of such a committee is aimed at bypassing the
existing criminal and civil laws to shorten the present
time-consuming process for protecting Thai workers' rights,
according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
In the past, foreign executives were able to flee the country
before they were made to face their responsibilities for the
affected Thai employees under Thai law.
</P>
<P>
Eden Group, a major European-owned garment factory, has shut
down its operation in Thailand, leaving more than 300 workers
behind without any compensation, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry last week said that some 40,000 workers are
expected to lose their jobs this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
