<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Hotels See Continued Slowdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Thai hotels continued to face
falling occupancy rates and lower room revenues this year, even in
the southern part of the country where hotels have not experienced
such serious problems over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
According to the Thai Hotels Association, from January to May,
hotels in southern Thailand reported the lowest occupancy rate in
the country, averaging 50 percent, down 2 percent compared with
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Hotels around Bangkok underwent the significant impact of the
slowdown with an average occupancy rate of 56 percent posted,
dropping 6.2 percent, the biggest decreasing margin around the
country.
</P>
<P>
Room revenues also dropped due to lower occupancy rates around
the country, despite the increased tourist arrivals.
</P>
<P>
In Bangkok, the total room revenues reported 8.2 percent lower.
In other provinces, the average decline was between five and six
percent, but in the south it was three percent.
</P>
<P>
If the situation does not turn better, there could be layoffs
in the hotel industry in the country, which employs some 400,000
people, warned Charnchai Satayaprasert, deputy chairman of the
association.
</P>
<P>
Charnchai predicted that for the rest of the year, occupancy
rates would be lower, or at best remain the same as last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
