<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Revoking China's MFN Damages Dialogue: White House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- White House National Security
Adviser Sandy Berger warned Congress today that revoking Most
Favored Nation (MFN) trading status for China could damage the
"strategic dialogue" between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He made the warning in a prepared speech for delivery tonight
to the Council of Foreign Relations in New York.
</P>
<P>
"It would close one of the world's emerging markets to our
exports. And it would drastically weaken Hong Kong, which handles
over 50 percent of U.S.-China trade," Berger said in the speech.
</P>
<P>
It was the latest warning from senior officials of the Clinton
administration as Congress began its annual debate on whether to
renew China's MFN status.
</P>
<P>
Responding to some congressmen who have expressed their
opposition to the extension of China's MFN, Berger said they were
"destroying our economic relations with China."
</P>
<P>
"Treating China as our enemy could well make China our enemy,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Berger emphasized that the U.S. interests would be "far better
served by increasing cooperation" with China, rather than by
severing the normal trade relations.
</P>
<P>
"That is the course this administration has chosen," he said.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton has decided to renew China's MFN, but
some congressmen are opposed to the decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
