<HEADLINE> Chinese DM Calls for Stronger Military Links With Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Defense Minister Chi
Haotian called for stronger military links between his country and
Ukraine, hoping that cooperation in military equipment and
technology can be carried out alongside with the overall
development of the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in talks with his Ukrainian counterpart,
Alexander Kuzmuk.
</P>
<P>
Chi, who is also vice-chairman of China's Central Military
Commission and state councillor, arrived in Kiev today for a
five-day visit.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Kuzmuk, Chi said the two countries have
enjoyed traditional friendship despite a long geographic distance.
</P>
<P>
He said China attaches importance to developing relations with
Ukraine because friendly relations based on the five principles of
peaceful coexistence are not only in the interests of both
countries, but also conducive to world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
Chi said the common task of both sides is to implement the
agreements signed by the two governments to consolidate
cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
He said China also attaches importance to relations between
the two armies. He hoped that relations between the two armies and
cooperation in military equipment and technology can be developed
alongside with the overall bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Kuzmuk said his country pursues a non-nuclear, neutral,
independent and non-bloc foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
He admired China's economic achievements and the achievements
of the People's Liberation Army in its modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
Kuzmuk said Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma's "historic"
visit to China in 1995 opened a new chapter in the bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
He said Chi's visit will push the bilateral relations further
ahead.
</P>
<P>
Chi is the highest-ranking Chinese military leader who has ever
visited the former Soviet republic.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese general, who had visited Belarus, will fly to
Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
