<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Foreign Trade National Bank of Mexico
(Bancomext) granted this week credits for 19.8 million dollars to
Central American entrepreneurs interested in acquiring Mexican
goods.
</P>
<P>
Samuel Lira, Bancomext representative for Costa Rica, Panama,
and Nicaragua, said the credits will be disbursed through private
banks and were placed with "very competitive" rates of interest,
attractive for the region entrepreneurs who make business with
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Mexican government will create a new entity
that will administer the risks in emissions of foreign debt, as
stated by the Mexican Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The new office, which will be named "Area of Administration of
Liabilities Risks" will be a branch of the Finance Ministry and
will be in charge of designing the mechanisms for the emission of
foreign debt in the international financial markets.
</P>
<P>
According to the Finance Ministry authorities, this area is
necessary because Mexico needs a better planning for its
emissions, after the damages caused by the crisis started in
December of 1994 and maintained until 1995 have been surmounted.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The price of wheat flour for bakery was reduced 4.6
percent Tuesday in Cost Rica, the second price reduction of this
year, said the Harina de Centroamerica manufacturing company.
</P>
<P>
The price reduction was attributed to more efficiency in the
imports of wheat, said Jorge Villalobos, the manager of the
company. With the price drop the price of a bag of wheat went from
19.3 dollars to 18 dollars.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Uruguayan manufacturing industry registered a
4 percent growth during the first quarter of the year, said the
National Statistics Institute.
</P>
<P>
The increase was accompanied for the first time in more than
two years, by a slight increase of 1.2 percent of the personnel
occupied by the sector, although a drop of 1 percent in the worked
hours was observed.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The production of the main cultivations in
Uruguay reached during the 1996-1997 cycle a total of 2.365
million tons, a 28.5 percent increase over the previous period.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture and Livestock Statistics Direction (DIEA), said
the wheat harvest increased 65 percent, corn 27 percent, rice 20
percent, and sorgum 19 percent. The four products lead the
harvests in Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Colombian sugar production reached during
the first three months of the year 591,926 tons, a 4.67 percent
drop compared to the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The reduction was attributed to unfavorable weather conditions
for the sugar cane harvest, including a very cold winter that has
compacted the soils, said the Sugar Cane Growers Association in a
report published today by the press.
</P>
<P>
Exports dropped 18.31 percent during the period because of a
2.3 percent increase in the domestic consuming and the drop in
production. enditem


nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
