<HEADLINE> Kuerten Moves into French Open Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's Gustavo Kuerten swept into
the men's singles final at the French Open with a hard-fought
victory over Belgian qualifier Filip Dewulf here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kuerten, the first Brazilian to enter the final in slam era,
defeated Dewulf 6-1, 3-6, 6-1, 7-6 (7-4) in two hours and 13
minutes.
</P>
<P>
Kuerten, who took the scalps of defending champion Yevgeny
Kafelnikov, Austria's 1995 titleholder Thomas Muster, dangerous
Ukranian Andrei Medvedev, Sweden's Jonas Bjorkman and Slava
Dosedel of the Czech Republic on his way to the semi-final, now
plays Sergi Bruguera of Spain.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old Spaniard moved one match away from a third
French Open singles crown when he saw off a magnificent challenge
from Australia's Patrick Rafter to score a 6-7 (6/8) 6-1, 7-5, 7-6
(7/1) win.
</P>
<P>
The match, playing in sweltering heat, lasted two hours 52
minutes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
