<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine tax revenue reached in May the
unprecedented amount of 4.614 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
May revenue from taxes, custom duties, and social security
surpassed April's by 17.3 percent and 28.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The increase in May was due to the maturities of the taxes on
income, which is not expected to repeat the next month.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- The Colombia poultry sector will grow from
three to four percent this year, a low level compared to the nine
to 10 percent rates in the past.
</P>
<P>
The drop in the prices of poultry favors consumers but not
producers, said Diego Miguel Sierra Botero, president of the
National Federation of Poultry Producers.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean mining output grew 8.6 percent in April,
compared to the same month of 1996, said the National Statistics
Institute.
</P>
<P>
With this result the mining output grew 8.4 percent during the
January-April period.
</P>
<P>
Copper production reached 273,516 tons in april, a 9.8 percent
compared to the same month of last year.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Cable and Wireless British company started
Wednesday telephony operations in Panama after acquiring for 652
million dollars, making up 49 percent of the stock in the
privatization of the state-owned Intel company.
</P>
<P>
British chief executive officer Richard Brown said the
acquisition stregthens the C&AMP;W position in the Caribbean.
</P>
