<HEADLINE> Tombs From Different Dynasties Unearthed in Henan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Nine brick tombs from the Han
(206 BC-220 AD), Tang (618-907) and Northern Song (960-1127)
dynasties have been excavated in the city of Yongcheng in central
China's Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
Of the burial articles, Chinese archaeologists value textile
tools and bronze mirrors from the Han Dynasty, porcelain from the
Tang dynasty, and coins from the Tang and Song dynasties.
</P>
<P>
Yongcheng, first inhabited some 4,000 years ago, was named for
a county in the Sui Dynasty (589-618).
</P>
<P>
It has been in the limelight in recent years, when rare relics
such as a jade burial suit with gold thread and exquisite wall
paintings were unearthed from local ducal tombs of the Western Han
Dynasty (206 BC-24 AD). 
</P>
</TEXT>
