<DOCNO> XIE19970607.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Crisis for Giant Pandas Alleviating (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The widespread natural death of
China's bamboo forests created a food crisis for wild giant pandas
fourteen years ago.
</P>
<P>
But zoologists in Minshan Prefecture, in northwest China's
Gansu Province, have discovered that giant pandas are eating
second-growth bamboo, which first appeared in 1989 in scarce
amounts. Bamboo has a growth cycle ranging from 15 to 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The "new" bamboo is now as high as 80 centimeters to one meter in
Wolong, China's largest giant panda natural reserve, located in
southwestern Sichuan Province, where one-tenth of the country's
giant pandas live.
</P>
<P>
"The bamboo will soon be ripe for eating by the giant
pandas. By then, their food shortage will be alleviated," said
Alan Taylor, a zoologist and botanist from the University of
Pennsylvania, who has come to China every year since 1983 to study
the bamboo and forests as habitats for the giant panda.
</P>
<P>
Giant pandas generally don't eat young bamboo shoots, Taylor
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
In other natural reserves, newly-grown bamboo can be provided
as food for giant pandas in the near future, the expert said.
</P>
<P>
There are currently only about 1,000 giant pandas in the world,
mainly living in the provinces of Sichuan, Gansu, and
Shaanxi. Sichuan claims about 80 percent of the giant pandas,
which are known as "living fossils."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970607.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
