<DOCNO> XIE19970607.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Crisis for Giant Pandas Alleviated (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A study by the World Wildlife Fund in the mid-1980s revealed
that there are about 30 varieties of bamboo that can be eaten by
giant pandas in their habitats. At the time, there were more than
560,000 hectares of bamboo and a storage supply of over 16.8
million tons.
</P>
<P>
But in the next two or three years, support will be needed for
the giant pandas' food supply, Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
Bamboo blossoms every 45 to 55 years. The most recent crop was
in 1983, when about a quarter of the wild giant pandas faced
starvation.
</P>
<P>
The situation attracted worldwide attention. In China, a
national donation campaign was launched, encompassing students
through the elderly.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, the Chinese government has taken a number
of steps to protect giant pandas, including:
</P>
<P>
-- setting up special areas where the pandas can be fed and
restored to health, and then returned to nature;
</P>
<P>
-- organizing disaster-relief teams to re-locate giant pandas
to a new environment with enough bamboo; and,
</P>
<P>
-- supplying food to giant pandas, such as meat, corn, and
sugarcanes.
</P>
<P>
So far, China has built 14 nature reserves for giant
pandas. However, experts point out, the survival of the giant
panda population depends to the greatest extent on regenerated
bamboo forests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970607.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hunan Uses Spiders for Insect Control on Tea Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- In an environmentally-friendly
form of insect control, Hunan Province, one of China's major tea
production bases, is replacing pesticides with spiders to wipe out
bugs that endanger the growth of profitable tea trees.
</P>
<P>
So far, tea produced by eight tea tree farms in Hunan has been
state certified as having especially healthful qualities.
</P>
<P>
In the past, chemical pesticides had been widely used to
eradicate the nearly ten types of insects that threaten the trees.
</P>
<P>
To eliminate the use of chemicals, biologists here caught
spiders and some other kinds of natural enemies of the tea tree
insects and raised them on the tea farms.
</P>
<P>
At Lanling Tea Farm, densely-spun spider webs are visible among
the tree branches, where spiders crawl about and munch on bugs.
</P>
<P>
Huang Houren, head of the farm, said 47 varieties of spiders
have been used to kill insects on the farm's 33.3 hectares of
trees.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, he invited eight experts from the Institute of Plant
Protection to battle the bugs in his trees with chemicals. The
experts also taught Huang how to raise spiders in vast tea tree
planting areas.
</P>
<P>
Huang said that his farm has established a strong spider
community which effectively protects the trees. He said that since
1993, no chemicals have been sprayed on his tea trees, and four
varieties of tea produced there have received state "green food"
certificates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970607.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Proposes to Establish a New Angola Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 6 (xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today proposed to set up a new U.N. Angola mission for a
period of seven months beginning 1 July after its current
peacekeeping operation ends by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
The new operation, which will be known as the UN Observer
Mission in Angola, is aimed to consolidate the peace process in
the country and to guide the demobilization of the UNITA soliders.
</P>
<P>
Annan, in his report to the Security Council, noted that the
peace process in the country showed significant progress, which
included the establishment of a coalition government, and the
normalization of state administration throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
But he emphasized that the UN presence is still needed to guide
the demobilization of the former rebel UNITA soliders and to
monitor the rising tensions in the northern part of the country.
He said that the demobilization process is moving at a very slow
pace.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the United Nations has about 5,000 troops, military
observers and civilian police in Angola, known as the United
Nations Angola Verification Mission III. It was established to
monitor the implementation of the Lusaka Protocol signed in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
