internationally," said John Roth, Nortel's president and chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
"As the future unfolds, and as Nortel expands globally, we will
also continue to grow Canada's reputation as a centre of global
expertise in communications," he said during a ceremony marking
the announcement.
</P>
<P>
Nortel stands as the world's sixth largest telecommunications
equipment supplier. It spends 1.8 billion dollars on research and
development, which accounts for 20 percent of all industrial R&AMP;D
in Canada.
</P>
<P>
Nortel employs 22,000 people in Canada, and 68,000 worldwide.
In 1996, it posted revenues of 12.8 billion dollars. 
