<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Concerned over Violence in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan expressed concern on Friday at the reports of the recent
violent incidents in Indonesia-ruled East Timor.
</P>
<P>
At least 34 people have been reported killed as a result of
attacks by separatists seeking to disrupt Indonesia's May 29
general elections in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has never recognized Indonesia's authority
over the territory, which it invaded in 1975 after the departure
of Portugal and annexed the following year.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General has called on all parties concerned to
exercise restraint," said U.N. Spokesman Fred Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
He said the Secretary-General is scheduled to hold a meeting
with the foreign ministers of Indonesia and Portugal on 19 and 20
June in New York on the question of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
It is one of the series of meetings aimed at finding an
internationally acceptable solution to the issue. They were
initiated in 1983 by then Secretary-General Javier Perez de Guellar
of Peru.  
</P>
</TEXT>
