<HEADLINE> Accord Signed Linking Rail Tracks Between </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 6 (Xinhua) - An agreement to reintegrate the
railway system of former Serb-controlled Eastern Slavonia with
that of Croatia was signed on Friday, local press reported.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed by representatives of Croatian Railways,
local Serbs and UN Transitional Administration in Eastern Slavonia
(UNTAS) which is temporarily governing the region before Croatia
resumes sovereignty in the middle of next month.
</P>
<P>
Souren Seraydarian, deputy head of UNTAS, said that the signing
of the document represents another important step forward in the
peaceful reintegration of the region to Croatia, following local
elections and introduction of Croatian currency earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Croatian railway company also promises
to retain Serb rail workers working in the region, which is a
major crossroad linking the eastern-south part with the rest of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
But although some demining work has been done, it is estimated
that more than 100 million U.S. dollars have to be invested to
repair the railways damaged during the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
