<HEADLINE> US Consumer Credit Increases Quickly in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Consumer credit outstanding in
the U.S. increased by a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 7.6
percent in April, much quicker than the rate in March, the U.S.
Federal Reserve (Fed) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The increase followed an increase of a 3 percent rate in March,
the lowest pace so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The growth of consumer credit in April was boosted by an upturn
in auto loans which gained by 12.7 percent following a decline of
2.7 percent in the month earlier. The amount of auto loans reached
379.5 billion dollars in April.
</P>
<P>
Revolving loans including the credit card was up by 4.3 percent
in the month, totaling 484.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other credit increased to 356.9 billion dollars, gaining by a
rate of 6.6 percent and slower than the 8 percent pace in March.
</P>
<P>
The total U.S. consumer credit increased to 1,220.9 billion
dollars in April, the U.S. Fed said.
</P>
<P>
In the first two months of the year, U.S. consumer credit had
gained by 10.3 percent in January and 6.7 percent in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
